%F A003500 a(n) = ( 2 + sqrt(3) )^n + ( 2 - sqrt(3) )^n.
%F A003500 a(n) = 2*A001075(n).
%F A003500 G.f.: 2*(1 - 2*x)/(1 - 4*x + x^2). _Simon Plouffe_ in his 1992 dissertation.
%F A003500 a(n) = A001835(n) + A001835(n+1).
%F A003500 a(n) = trace of n-th power of the 2 X 2 matrix [1 2 / 1 3]. - _Gary W. Adamson_, Jun 30 2003 [corrected by _Joerg Arndt_, Jun 18 2020]
%F A003500 From the addition formula, a(n+m) = a(n)*a(m) - a(m-n), it is easy to derive multiplication formulas, such as: a(2*n) = (a(n))^2 - 2, a(3*n) = (a(n))^3 - 3*(a(n)), a(4*n) = (a(n))^4 - 4*(a(n))^2 + 2, a(5*n) = (a(n))^5 - 5*(a(n))^3 + 5*(a(n)), a(6*n) = (a(n))^6 - 6*(a(n))^4 + 9*(a(n))^2 - 2, etc. The absolute values of the coefficients in the expansions are given by the triangle A034807. - _John Blythe Dobson_, Nov 04 2007
%F A003500 a(n) = 2*A001353(n+1) - 4*A001353(n). - _R. J. Mathar_, Nov 16 2007
%F A003500 From _Peter Bala_, Jan 06 2013: (Start)
%F A003500 Let F(x) = Product_{n=0..infinity} (1 + x^(4*n + 1))/(1 + x^(4*n + 3)). Let alpha = 2 - sqrt(3). This sequence gives the simple continued fraction expansion of 1 + F(alpha) = 2.24561 99455 06551 88869 ... = 2 + 1/(4 + 1/(14 + 1/(52 + ...))). Cf. A174500.
%F A003500 Also F(-alpha) = 0.74544 81786 39692 68884 ... has the continued fraction representation 1 - 1/(4 - 1/(14 - 1/(52 - ...))) and the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((4 - 2) + 1/(1 + 1/((14 - 2) + 1/(1 + 1/((52 - 2) + 1/(1 + ...))))))).
%F A003500 F(alpha)*F(-alpha) has the simple continued fraction expansion 1/(1 + 1/((4^2 - 4) + 1/(1 + 1/((14^2 - 4) + 1/(1 + 1/((52^2 - 4) + 1/(1 + ...))))))).
%F A003500 (End)
%F A003500 a(2^n) = A003010(n). - _John Blythe Dobson_, Mar 10 2014
%F A003500 a(n) = [x^n] ( (1 + 4*x + sqrt(1 + 8*x + 12*x^2))/2 )^n for n >= 1. - _Peter Bala_, Jun 23 2015
%F A003500 E.g.f.: 2*exp(2*x)*cosh(sqrt(3)*x). - _Ilya Gutkovskiy_, Apr 27 2016
%F A003500 a(n) = Sum_{k=0..floor(n/2)} (-1)^k*n*(n - k - 1)!/(k!*(n - 2*k)!)*4^(n - 2*k) for n >= 1. - _Peter Luschny_, May 10 2016
%F A003500 From _Peter Bala_, Oct 15 2019: (Start)
%F A003500 a(n) = trace(M^n), where M is the 2 X 2 matrix [0, 1; -1, 4].
%F A003500 Consequently the Gauss congruences hold: a(n*p^k) = a(n*p^(k-1)) ( mod p^k ) for all prime p and positive integers n and k. See Zarelua and also Stanley (Ch. 5, Ex. 5.2(a) and its solution).
%F A003500 2*Sum_{n >= 1} 1/( a(n) - 6/a(n) ) = 1.
%F A003500 6*Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/( a(n) + 2/a(n) ) = 1.
%F A003500 8*Sum_{n >= 1} 1/( a(n) + 24/(a(n) - 12/(a(n))) ) = 1.
%F A003500 8*Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/( a(n) + 8/(a(n) + 4/(a(n))) ) = 1.
%F A003500 Series acceleration formulas for sums of reciprocals:
%F A003500 Sum_{n >= 1} 1/a(n) = 1/2 - 6*Sum_{n >= 1} 1/(a(n)*(a(n)^2 - 6)),
%F A003500 Sum_{n >= 1} 1/a(n) = 1/8 + 24*Sum_{n >= 1} 1/(a(n)*(a(n)^2 + 12)),
%F A003500 Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/a(n) = 1/6 + 2*Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/(a(n)*(a(n)^2 + 2)) and
%F A003500 Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/a(n) = 1/8 + 8*Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/(a(n)*(a(n)^2 + 12)).
%F A003500 Sum_{n >= 1} 1/a(n) = ( theta_3(2-sqrt(3))^2 - 1 )/4 = 0.34770 07561 66992 06261 .... See Borwein and Borwein, Proposition 3.5 (i), p.91.
%F A003500 Sum_{n >= 1} (-1)^(n+1)/a(n) = ( 1 - theta_3(sqrt(3)-2)^2 )/4. Cf. A003499 and A153415. (End)
%F A003500 a(n) = tan(Pi/12)^n + tan(5*Pi/12)^n. - _Greg Dresden_, Oct 01 2020
%F A003500 From _Wolfdieter Lang_, Sep 06 2021: (Start)
%F A003500 a(n) = S(n, 4) - S(n-2, 4) = 2*T(n, 2), for n >= 0, with S and T Chebyshev polynomials, with S(-1, x) = 0 and S(-2, x) = -1. S(n, 4) = A001353(n+1), for n >= -1, and T(n, 2) = A001075(n).
%F A003500 a(2*k) = A067902(k), a(2*k+1) = 4*A001570(k+1), for k >= 0. (End)
%F A003500 a(n) = sqrt(2 + 2*A011943(n+1)) = sqrt(2 + 2*A102344(n+1)), n>0. - _Ralf Steiner_, Sep 23 2021
%F A003500 Sum_{n>=1} arctan(3/a(n)^2) = Pi/6 - arctan(1/3) = A019673 - A105531 (Ohtskua, 2024). - _Amiram Eldar_, Aug 29 2024
